ve and promote development, retreats and other efforts to build skills and renew commitment to mission to provide best financial services to clients. Wage increases with promotions and annual bonus.ConsPartners don't always agree and send mixed signals; teams vary in efforts to promote and secure better wages for staff; pressure to keep or increase assets is constant and not always in clients best interest. Expect terminations in market downturns. More senior females have left the firm.Advice to ManagementShare the wealth. Provide more on-going feedback. Follow the decisions of the investment committee and don't send mixed signals to employees. Allow different opinions without feeling threatened. Keep criticism private.Share on FacebookShare on TwitterShare on WhatsAppShare via EmailCopy LinkLink Copied!Flag as InappropriateFlag as InappropriateHelpful (0) Sullivan, Bruyette, Speros & Blayney Response seconds agoEdit • Delete Sullivan, Bruyette, Speros & Blayney 2015-11-08 06:12 PSTReviews > Sullivan, Bruyette, Speros & Blayney RSS Feed</>EmbedCloseOutline of two peoples' headsWork in HR or Marketing?Grow your employer brandGet a free employer accountCloseOutline of two peoples' headsWork in HR or Marketing?Grow your employer brandGet a free employer accountCompanies to Explore Company BenefitsDoctor's valiseThere are currently no benefit reviews for this company.Add Benefits Review Job Seekers Also ViewedBMO Harris Bank ReviewsStarStarStarStarStar 597 ReviewsBMO Financial Group ReviewsStarStarStarStarStar 1,609 ReviewsJ.P. Morgan ReviewsStarStarStarStarStar 12,377 ReviewsPNC Financial Services Group ReviewsStarStarStarStarStar 3,620 ReviewsThe Blackstone Group ReviewsStarStarStarStarStar 128 ReviewsEdward Jones ReviewsStarStarStarStarStar 1,828 Reviews Related Job SearchAnalyst jobsAnalyst salaries ($67k)Vice President jobsVice President salaries ($148k)Associate jobsAssociate salaries ($92k)Investment Banking Analyst jobsInvestment Banking Analyst salaries ($77k)I